1
00:00:00,130 --> 00:00:01,849
On this episode of China Uncensored,

2
00:00:01,849 --> 00:00:04,500
is China gaming bitcoin?

3
00:00:08,800 --> 00:00:09,860
Hi, welcome to China Uncensored,

4
00:00:09,860 --> 00:00:11,620
I’m your host Chris Chappell.

5
00:00:11,620 --> 00:00:12,620
Bitcoin!

6
00:00:12,620 --> 00:00:14,150
The money of the future.

7
00:00:14,150 --> 00:00:15,150
Maybe.

8
00:00:15,150 --> 00:00:16,250
Or it could all crash and burn.

9
00:00:16,250 --> 00:00:18,140
Depends who you ask.

10
00:00:18,140 --> 00:00:20,360
For those of you unfamiliar with it,

11
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:22,820
Bitcoin is a peer-to-peer cryptocurrency.

12
00:00:22,820 --> 00:00:27,159
Which is not how this guy pays you for dinner.

13
00:00:27,159 --> 00:00:28,560
Cryptocurrency uses cryptography

14
00:00:28,560 --> 00:00:30,229
to secure its transactions

15
00:00:30,229 --> 00:00:32,630
and to create more of the currency.

16
00:00:32,630 --> 00:00:34,860
Cryptography secures information in code,

17
00:00:34,860 --> 00:00:37,030
like the famous Enigma machines

18
00:00:37,030 --> 00:00:39,580
used by the Nazis during World War II.

19
00:00:39,580 --> 00:00:42,080
Nowadays, cryptography is done by computers

20
00:00:42,080 --> 00:00:44,820
using incredibly complex math.

21
00:00:44,820 --> 00:00:46,560
Which unlike the Enigma code,

22
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:48,810
can't be solved by Britain's greatest minds,

23
00:00:48,810 --> 00:00:50,960
Sherlock Holmes and Elizabeth Swann.

24
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:53,540
Modern cryptography lets Bitcoin

25
00:00:53,540 --> 00:00:55,930
operate independently from a central authority,

26
00:00:55,930 --> 00:00:57,500
like a government or a bank,

27
00:00:57,500 --> 00:00:58,550
because you don't need a third party

28
00:00:58,550 --> 00:01:00,820
to validate the Bitcoin transaction.

29
00:01:00,820 --> 00:01:03,360
And transactions can be done anonymously.

30
00:01:03,360 --> 00:01:05,329
Bitcoin has been described as

31
00:01:05,329 --> 00:01:08,160
the world’s most democratic currency.

32
00:01:08,160 --> 00:01:10,400
So obviously it’s been thriving in—

33
00:01:10,400 --> 00:01:11,540
you guessed it—

34
00:01:11,540 --> 00:01:12,540
China.

35
00:01:12,740 --> 00:01:14,620
According to Coin Telegraph,

36
00:01:14,620 --> 00:01:16,800
“the majority of Bitcoin trading,

37
00:01:16,810 --> 00:01:20,700
estimated from 50 percent to 98 percent,

38
00:01:20,700 --> 00:01:22,899
takes place in China.”

39
00:01:22,899 --> 00:01:24,509
This creates a problem.

40
00:01:24,509 --> 00:01:26,219
In theory, Bitcoin can’t be controlled

41
00:01:26,219 --> 00:01:27,429
by any government.

42
00:01:27,429 --> 00:01:28,659
But in practice,

43
00:01:28,659 --> 00:01:30,469
the Chinese Communist Party can have

44
00:01:30,469 --> 00:01:31,799
a huge influence

45
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:34,469
on the global price of Bitcoin.

46
00:01:34,469 --> 00:01:35,720
So if you own Bitcoin,

47
00:01:35,729 --> 00:01:37,480
well, the value of your money can

48
00:01:37,490 --> 00:01:39,289
be heavily influenced by the whims

49
00:01:39,289 --> 00:01:42,920
of the world’s largest authoritarian regime.

50
00:01:42,920 --> 00:01:45,470
Take that, democratic currency!

51
00:01:45,470 --> 00:01:48,140
Take what happened in 2013 as an example.

52
00:01:48,149 --> 00:01:49,899
In early September that year,

53
00:01:49,899 --> 00:01:53,560
one Bitcoin was worth around 100 US dollars.

54
00:01:53,560 --> 00:01:54,840
By late November,

55
00:01:54,840 --> 00:01:56,539
that price had skyrocketed

56
00:01:56,540 --> 00:01:59,959
to more than 1,000 dollars per Bitcoin.

57
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:01,420
And then overnight,

58
00:02:01,420 --> 00:02:03,440
it came crashing down.

59
00:02:03,450 --> 00:02:04,810
China’s central bank,

60
00:02:04,810 --> 00:02:06,229
the People’s Bank of China,

61
00:02:06,229 --> 00:02:08,200
told financial institutions in China

62
00:02:08,200 --> 00:02:10,580
to suspend trading in Bitcoin

63
00:02:10,580 --> 00:02:13,170
because it “doesn't have ‘real meaning’

64
00:02:13,170 --> 00:02:14,920
and lacks legal protections.”

65
00:02:14,920 --> 00:02:17,500
Funny that those same things

66
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:18,820
didn't stop the Chinese regime

67
00:02:18,820 --> 00:02:20,660
from encouraging people to speculate

68
00:02:20,660 --> 00:02:22,420
in China's stock markets.

69
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:24,080
But back to Bitcoin.

70
00:02:24,080 --> 00:02:25,240
In two weeks,

71
00:02:25,240 --> 00:02:27,890
Bitcoin lost over half its value.

72
00:02:27,890 --> 00:02:28,890
It took a full year

73
00:02:28,890 --> 00:02:31,320
before the price bottomed out.

74
00:02:31,320 --> 00:02:32,320
Something similar happened again

75
00:02:32,320 --> 00:02:33,960
in February this year.

76
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:35,370
The People’s Bank of China met with

77
00:02:35,370 --> 00:02:38,030
three of China’s biggest Bitcoin exchanges,

78
00:02:38,030 --> 00:02:41,760
BTC China, Huobi, and OKCoin.

79
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:44,160
The exchanges then stopped Bitcoin withdrawals

80
00:02:44,160 --> 00:02:45,960
for four months.

81
00:02:45,960 --> 00:02:47,640
The exchanges recently lifted the ban,

82
00:02:47,640 --> 00:02:49,000
but during the suspension,

83
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:50,430
the global price of Bitcoin

84
00:02:50,430 --> 00:02:51,630
dropped again,

85
00:02:51,630 --> 00:02:54,360
though not as much as in 2013.

86
00:02:54,360 --> 00:02:55,630
So why has the Chinese regime

87
00:02:55,630 --> 00:02:57,500
been targeting Bitcoin?

88
00:02:57,500 --> 00:02:59,080
Besides it being a democratic currency?

89
00:02:59,080 --> 00:03:01,180
There are a few reasons.

90
00:03:01,180 --> 00:03:03,580
First, Chinese people can use Bitcoin

91
00:03:03,580 --> 00:03:05,440
to get their money out of China.

92
00:03:05,440 --> 00:03:07,820
You see, the Chinese regime has limits

93
00:03:07,820 --> 00:03:09,160
on the amount of foreign currency

94
00:03:09,160 --> 00:03:11,230
people in China can buy—

95
00:03:11,230 --> 00:03:12,230
because they’re worried about

96
00:03:12,230 --> 00:03:13,260
rich Chinese people

97
00:03:13,260 --> 00:03:14,870
moving their money out

98
00:03:14,870 --> 00:03:16,700
and then fleeing the country.

99
00:03:16,700 --> 00:03:20,480
But Chinese investors can buy Bitcoin in China,

100
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:22,600
and then later exchange that for foreign currency

101
00:03:22,600 --> 00:03:25,080
in any amount they want.

102
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:27,170
Huge fortunes that might have been made through,

103
00:03:27,170 --> 00:03:28,920
I don’t know,

104
00:03:28,930 --> 00:03:29,930
corruption,

105
00:03:29,930 --> 00:03:31,410
could be safely stored out of reach

106
00:03:31,410 --> 00:03:34,329
of pesky Chinese investigators.

107
00:03:34,329 --> 00:03:36,170
And that was why China’s central bank

108
00:03:36,170 --> 00:03:38,570
started investigating Bitcoin exchanges

109
00:03:38,570 --> 00:03:39,950
back in February,

110
00:03:39,950 --> 00:03:41,930
and threatened to shut down exchanges

111
00:03:41,930 --> 00:03:43,270
that violated rules on

112
00:03:43,270 --> 00:03:45,120
“foreign exchange management,

113
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:46,120
money laundering,

114
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:47,210
and payment and settlement.”

115
00:03:47,210 --> 00:03:48,930
But it’s unclear how much money

116
00:03:48,930 --> 00:03:50,840
is actually being moved out of China

117
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:52,180
through Bitcoin.

118
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:53,770
Bitcoin transactions in China

119
00:03:53,770 --> 00:03:55,340
are not anonymous,

120
00:03:55,340 --> 00:03:56,340
since you have to link

121
00:03:56,340 --> 00:03:57,340
a Chinese bank card

122
00:03:57,340 --> 00:03:59,010
to your Bitcoin account.

123
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:00,060
You could move a few hundred

124
00:04:00,060 --> 00:04:01,690
thousand yuan into Bitcoin,

125
00:04:01,690 --> 00:04:04,620
but larger amounts would attract attention.

126
00:04:04,620 --> 00:04:05,740
So why is there so much

127
00:04:05,750 --> 00:04:07,360
Bitcoin trading in China?

128
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:09,800
Well, that brings us to the second reason

129
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:11,630
the Chinese regime is so interested

130
00:04:11,630 --> 00:04:13,390
in Bitcoin.

131
00:04:13,390 --> 00:04:14,560
Earlier I mentioned people speculating

132
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:16,320
in China's stock markets,

133
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:17,320
and since those markets

134
00:04:17,320 --> 00:04:18,910
have cooled down,

135
00:04:18,910 --> 00:04:19,910
guess where people

136
00:04:19,910 --> 00:04:21,200
are putting their money now?

137
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:22,870
You see, in China,

138
00:04:22,870 --> 00:04:23,870
there's not a lot of places

139
00:04:23,870 --> 00:04:25,730
people can invest their money.

140
00:04:25,730 --> 00:04:26,889
Which leads to things like

141
